=========================================
C++ MAP (Associative Container)
INTERVIEW PREPARATION NOTES
=========================================

1. What is map?
---------------

std::map is an associative container that stores data as:

key -> value

Example:

map<int, string> m;

m[1] = "John";
m[2] = "David";

Stores elements sorted by key.

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Implementation
--------------------------

Implemented using:

Red-Black Tree
(Self-Balancing Binary Search Tree)

Example:

        20
       /  \
      10   30
     /       \
    5         40

Properties:

✓ Keys always sorted
✓ Height balanced
✓ Search O(log n)
✓ Insert O(log n)
✓ Delete O(log n)

Interview Q:
How is std::map implemented internally?

Answer:
std::map is typically implemented using a Red-Black Tree, which is a self-balancing binary search tree.

-----------------------------------------

3. Key Characteristics
----------------------

✓ Stores key-value pairs
✓ Keys are unique
✓ Automatically sorted by key
✓ Fast search/insert/delete
✓ No duplicate keys

Example:

map<int,string> m;

m[1] = "A";
m[1] = "B";

Result:

1 -> B

Old value overwritten.

-----------------------------------------

4. Complexity
-------------

insert()          O(log n)
erase()           O(log n)
find()            O(log n)
count()           O(log n)

operator[]        O(log n)
at()              O(log n)

begin()           O(1)
size()            O(1)

-----------------------------------------

5. Why O(log n)?
----------------

Because map uses a balanced BST.

Each operation traverses tree height.

Balanced Tree Height:

log n

Therefore:

Search = O(log n)
Insert = O(log n)
Delete = O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

6. Ordered Container
--------------------

Map always keeps keys sorted.

Example:

map<int,string> m;

m[30] = "C";
m[10] = "A";
m[20] = "B";

Output:

10 A
20 B
30 C

Interview Q:
Does map maintain insertion order?

Answer:
No.
It maintains sorted order based on keys.

-----------------------------------------

7. operator[] vs at()
---------------------

operator[]

m[10]

If key does not exist:
Creates a new entry.

Example:

map<int,int> m;

m[5];

Now key 5 exists.

-----------------------------------------

at()

m.at(10);

If key not found:

Throws:
out_of_range exception

Interview Q:
Difference between operator[] and at()?

Answer:
operator[] inserts a default value if key doesn't exist, while at() throws an exception.

-----------------------------------------

8. find()
----------

auto it = m.find(20);

if(it != m.end())
{
    cout << it->second;
}

Complexity:

O(log n)

Interview Q:
Difference between find() and operator[]?

Answer:
find() does not insert a new element if key is absent.

-----------------------------------------

9. count()
-----------

m.count(10)

Returns:

1 -> key exists
0 -> key absent

Because keys are unique.

Example:

if(m.count(10))
{
   cout<<"Found";
}

-----------------------------------------

10. insert()
------------

m.insert({1,"John"});

Complexity:

O(log n)

If key already exists:

Insertion fails.

-----------------------------------------

11. erase()
-----------

m.erase(10);

Removes key 10.

Complexity:

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

12. Iterating Map
-----------------

for(auto &p : m)
{
    cout << p.first
         << " "
         << p.second
         << endl;
}

Output sorted by key.

-----------------------------------------

13. Custom Comparator
---------------------

Descending order:

map<int,string,greater<int>> m;

Output:

30
20
10

Interview Q:
How do you store keys in descending order?

Answer:
Use greater<> comparator.

-----------------------------------------

14. map vs unordered_map
------------------------

map
---
Red-Black Tree
Sorted
O(log n)

unordered_map
-------------
Hash Table
Not sorted
Average O(1)

Interview Q:
Difference between map and unordered_map?

Answer:
map keeps keys sorted and uses a Red-Black Tree. unordered_map uses hashing and provides average O(1) lookup but no ordering.

-----------------------------------------

15. map vs set
--------------

set
---
Stores only keys.

map
---
Stores key-value pairs.

Example:

set<int>

10
20
30

map<int,string>

10 -> A
20 -> B
30 -> C

